pst-d7d: keep multiconnectSlotDesignBOSL.scad working across BOSL2's
attachable() API drift (BOSL2 ae73c6d, "attachments update", 2024-09-27).

Two independent breaks, both introduced by ae73c6d and both hit on any
BOSL2 newer than 456fcd8 — which is every BOSL2 that carries the struct
functions mitufy openConnect needs (st-kls, pst-yr1):

1. VECTOR SPIN. ae73c6d tightened attachable() to assert is_finite(spin),
   but the two on-ramp cyl() calls pass spin=[90,0,180]. Hoisting the
   rotation to an outer rot([90,0,180]) and letting attachable() see the
   default scalar spin reproduces old BOSL2's transform exactly: for a
   centered cyl the old vector-spin path composed zrot(z)*yrot(y)*xrot(x),
   which is precisely rot([x,y,z]).

2. ZERO-RADIUS CONE ANCHOR. ae73c6d rewrote conical anchor math to use
   solve_ellipse(), which evaluates unit([0,0]) when r2 == 0 and trips
   assert(is_vector(v)) "Invalid vector". The four slot dimples are
   cylinder(r1=1.5*dimpleScale, r2=0) cones. Truncating the tip to
   r2 = 0.001*dimpleScale keeps solve_ellipse() non-degenerate; at
   0.0015mm the truncation is three orders of magnitude below both mesh
   ($fn=50) and print resolution.

Both edits are geometry-preserving: full-catalog STL A/B across the bump
showed 0 dimensional changes (pst-yr1 section b). Break 2 is only
revealed once break 1 is fixed, and note that break 1 fails *silently* on
Backer models — the failing subtree sits under diff(), so OpenSCAD drops
it and still writes a watertight-but-wrong STL (ego_lb6500 lost ~94% of
its multiconnect geometry this way). Drop this patch if QuackWorks
upstream ever moves off the vector-spin / zero-r2 syntax.

